The corresponding dose constants of 50, 100, 150 and 200 mgL−1 CIP were 0.25, 0.21, 0.19 and 0.14 kGy−1, respectively, which reduced with the increase of CIP concentration. The results could be ascribed to that more by-products were generated to compete with target contaminants for reactive species (·OH, eaq
                        −, and ·H) (Guo et al., 2017a). This also led to the augment of the calculated D0.5 and D0.9 when CIP concentration increased (Table 1
                        ).

According to the frontier orbital theory, the highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) were the most likely sites for chemical reactions. As shown in Fig. 8 a, the HOMO of CIP was mainly located on piperazine ring and quinolone moiety, which were prone to be attacked by OH·. In addition, Fukui function is a very important concept in the conceptual density functional theory, which has been widely used in prediction of reactive sites. Thus, the Fukui functions were employed to predict the possible reactive sites of nucleophilic attack (
f +
), electrophilic attack (
f −
) and radical attack (
f 0
) based on the DFT calculations (Fig. 8b). It was obvious that C28, O26, N10 could be easily attacked by radicals due to their higher condensed Fukui index (
f 0
) value (Pan et al., 2021). Moreover, main intermediates were found by LC-MS, of which molecular masses and possible structures were listed in Table 2 . Based on the above results, the possible pathway of CIP degradation in EBI&g-C3N4/CDs synergistic system was proposed (Fig. 8c).
